<img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-1687247 lazyload lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/Times-of-India-797x598.jpg" alt="" width="1280" height="960" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/Times-of-India-797x598.jpg 797w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/Times-of-India-320x240.jpg 320w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/Times-of-India-640x480.jpg 640w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/Times-of-India-600x450.jpg 600w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/Times-of-India.jpg 1200w" sizes="(max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px" /> Ovarian cancer is a treatable disease when recognized early before it begins to spread beyond the ovaries. However, the signs can be a bit deceptive, making like 9 out of 10 people not notice any discernible signs within the early stages. But there are a few unobtrusive side effects you ought to be concerned about. What are the risk factors to consider with ovarian cancer? With most types of cancers, there’s barely a way of knowing if one is vulnerable to getting the illness. Meanwhile, in reality, most ladies get it without a high chance. Although some reasons would increase the chances of getting ovarian cancer. Age Factor: in most cases and for everyone, age has a significant role to play in the body as one age. Middle-aged or older ladies are at risk of the illness. Additionally, if there is a close family member who has been diagnosed with ovarian cancer and any history of endometriosis. Again ethnicity has its influence, therefore women of Eastern and European origin should be mindful. Other cases of individuals likely to have ovarian cancer are people who have had other types of cancers such as breast, colorectal or uterine cancer. But thanks to science, there are modern treatments found to recoil tumours in ovarian cancer patients. This basic blood test may spare you from ovarian cancer and some other forms of cancer. One of the many early signs of ovarian cancer may appear like those of common health conditions such as urinary tract infections or irritable bowel syndrome. In that case, one is likely to be dismissive of such symptoms without taking a trip to the doctor. This type of stalling delays treatment and increases the chances of it spreading to other parts of the body. When this happens and sadly does in a large percentage of cases, it diminishes the survival rate in patients. Some of the symptoms that can go unnoticed include: Are you on your period and bloating is usually an obvious sign? Bloating can as well happen due to a type of food eaten. Where bloating becomes worrisome is in being persistent. Bloating could be a sign of ovarian cancer and should be reported to a medical professional. Abdominal and pelvic pain: This is one of such symptoms that is usually linked among most patients which they say is similar to having menstrual cramps. If this lingers, then extra medical attention should be given to it. Have you noticed a new pattern recently? This pertains to feeling like the bladder is full even after urinating or a burning feeling that is experienced while urinating. There is a routine change in bathroom usage that is accompanied by frequent urination, a sudden increase in constipation and diarrhoea. More subtle signs that your body speak to you that something might be wrong that are taken into consideration are, loss of appetite, ingestion, back pain, pain during sex and change in the menstrual cycle. Do they sound familiar? Have they been persistent? Why not try talking to a healthcare practitioner. Note that close similarity with many other conditions often leads to the wrong diagnosis. Hence throw all your questions at the doctors’ office.